RESULT: Audit tools may be vulnerable to unauthorized deletion. Ensure /sbin is owned by root with permissions 755 and all audit tools are present.</FINDING_DETAILS>
				<COMMENTS>Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/09/2026:

Answer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml
Key Name: XCP-ng
Index: 2

[ValidTrueComment]:
Audit tools may be vulnerable to unauthorized deletion on XCP-ng Dom0.

The automated check found that /sbin directory permissions are not properly restricted, or audit tool binaries are missing. Without proper directory-level protection, non-root users may be able to delete audit tools.

Remediation:
1. Verify /sbin ownership and permissions: chown root:root /sbin; chmod 755 /sbin
2. Reinstall missing audit tools: yum reinstall audit
3. Verify all audit binaries are present: rpm -V audit
4. Consider enabling immutable attribute on critical binaries: chattr +i /sbin/auditd (requires careful change management)

Contact the system administrator to restore audit tool integrity.

</COMMENTS>
