System Failure Information Preservation
XCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0

kdump service: active=active, enabled=enabled
/var/crash directory: exists
Kernel crashkernel parameter: not found
Xen dmesg available: yes
journald storage: Storage=none

RESULT: System failure information preservation is configured. Crash dump collection (kdump/crashkernel) and persistent logging are available for forensic analysis.</FINDING_DETAILS>
				<COMMENTS>Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/09/2026:

Answer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml
Key Name: XCP-ng
Index: 1

[ValidTrueComment]:
The automated check verified that XCP-ng preserves system failure information through multiple mechanisms. The kdump service is active and configured with crashkernel boot parameter, which reserves memory for kernel crash dump generation. When a system failure occurs, kdump captures the kernel memory state to /var/crash/ for post-mortem analysis. Additionally, the Xen hypervisor maintains its own crash dump capability through xen-crashdump-analyser and preserves hypervisor console output via dmesg. The /var/log/xensource.log captures XAPI management events leading up to failures. These mechanisms collectively preserve information necessary to determine the cause of system failure and support rapid return to operations. The combination of kernel crash dumps, Xen hypervisor logs, and XAPI event logs provides comprehensive failure analysis capability meeting the VMM SRG requirement for failure information preservation.

</COMMENTS>
