Remote Access Disconnect Capability
XCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0

SSH service enabled: enabled (can be stopped with: systemctl stop sshd)
iptables available: yes
Immediate block: iptables -A INPUT -j DROP (blocks all incoming)
xe session-logout: terminates XAPI sessions on demand
XAPI service: can be stopped with systemctl stop xapi

RESULT: XCP-ng provides multiple mechanisms to immediately disconnect or disable remote access: (1) systemctl stop sshd terminates all SSH connections; (2) iptables rules can block all incoming traffic immediately; (3) xe session-logout terminates individual XAPI sessions; (4) systemctl stop xapi disables management API access. Administrators have full capability to disconnect remote access.</FINDING_DETAILS>
				<COMMENTS>Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/09/2026:

Answer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml
Key Name: XCP-ng
Index: 1

[ValidTrueComment]:
The automated check verified that XCP-ng provides multiple mechanisms to immediately disconnect or disable remote access: (1) systemctl stop sshd terminates all SSH connections immediately; (2) iptables rules can block all incoming traffic (iptables -A INPUT -j DROP); (3) xe session-logout terminates individual XAPI sessions on demand; (4) systemctl stop xapi disables management API access. These mechanisms allow administrators to immediately disconnect remote access in response to security incidents. The iptables utility is available on the system, confirming firewall-based disconnection capability. This meets the VMM SRG requirement for immediate remote access disconnection.

</COMMENTS>
				<SEVERITY_OVERRIDE />
				<SEVERITY_JUSTIFICATION />
