Audit Account Enabling Actions
XCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0

auditd service: inactive
Audit rule for /etc/passwd: NOT configured
Audit rule for /etc/shadow: NOT configured
Audit rule for /etc/group: NOT configured
Audit rule for usermod/chage: NOT configured

RESULT: auditd is not properly configured to audit account enabling actions. The auditd service is not active. Enable with: systemctl enable --now auditd. Ensure audit rules monitor /etc/passwd, /etc/shadow, and /etc/group for write access: auditctl -w /etc/passwd -p wa -k identity; auditctl -w /etc/shadow -p wa -k identity; auditctl -w /etc/group -p wa -k identity</FINDING_DETAILS>
				<COMMENTS>Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/09/2026:

Answer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml
Key Name: XCP-ng
Index: 2

[ValidTrueComment]:
The automated check found that auditd is not properly configured to audit account enabling actions on XCP-ng. Either the auditd service is not active or audit rules do not monitor the identity files (/etc/passwd, /etc/shadow, /etc/group). To remediate: (1) Enable auditd: systemctl enable --now auditd; (2) Add audit rules: auditctl -w /etc/passwd -p wa -k identity; auditctl -w /etc/shadow -p wa -k identity; auditctl -w /etc/group -p wa -k identity; (3) Make rules persistent in /etc/audit/rules.d/identity.rules; (4) Reload rules: augenrules --load. These rules will capture all account enabling, disabling, creation, and removal events.

</COMMENTS>
				<SEVERITY_OVERRIDE />
				<SEVERITY_JUSTIFICATION />
