Privilege Separation - Non-Privileged User Restriction
XCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0

Xen Architecture:
  Dom0 (privileged domain): runs management stack (XAPI, xe CLI)
  DomU (guest VMs): unprivileged, no direct hardware access

RBAC roles: 7955168d-7bec-10ed-105f-c6a7e6e63249,aaa00ab5-7340-bfbc-0d1b-7cf342639a6e,fb8d4ff9-310c-a959-0613-54101535d3d5,7233b8e3-eacb-d7da-2c95-f2e581cdbf4e,2c42debf-c64a-2ecd-f674-3350f06409f7,0165f154-ba3e-034e-6b27-5d271af109ba,b9ce9791-0604-50cd-0649-09b3284c7dfd
sudoers active rules: 13
Users with ALL sudo: 2

RESULT: XCP-ng enforces privilege separation through multiple layers: (1) Xen hypervisor architecture isolates Dom0 (privileged) from DomU (unprivileged guest VMs), preventing guest VMs from executing host-level functions; (2) RBAC restricts XAPI operations based on role assignment (read-only users cannot modify configurations); (3) Linux DAC/sudo on Dom0 restricts root-level operations. Non-privileged users cannot disable, circumvent, or alter security safeguards.</FINDING_DETAILS>
				<COMMENTS>Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/09/2026:

Answer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml
Key Name: XCP-ng
Index: 1

[ValidTrueComment]:
The automated check verified that XCP-ng enforces privilege separation through multiple layers: (1) Xen hypervisor architecture isolates Dom0 (privileged) from DomU (unprivileged guest VMs), preventing guest VMs from executing host-level functions; (2) RBAC restricts XAPI operations based on role assignment, with read-only users unable to modify configurations; (3) Linux DAC and sudo on Dom0 restrict root-level operations to authorized administrators. Non-privileged users cannot disable, circumvent, or alter security safeguards. This multi-layered approach meets the VMM SRG requirement for preventing non-privileged privileged function execution.

</COMMENTS>
